<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Kobresia myosuroides </i>(a CNPS list 2.3 plant) is a caespitose sedge to 20 cm tall with a circumpolar range. It grows on bare rock, dry upland, and wetland conditions, including bogs and fens, throughout boreal North America. It is one of the disjunct Rocky Mountain plants found in the Convict Creek drainage of California on marble along with <i>Arctostaphylos uva-ursi, Draba lonchocarpa </i>var. <i>lonchocarpa, Pedicularis crenulata, </i>and <i>Salix brachycarpa </i>var. <i>brachycarpa </i>(Major and Bamberg 1963, 1967). Nearby, (RSA accession 695422) <i>K. myosuroides </i>grows with <i>Betula occidentalis, Carex scirpoidea </i>ssp. <i>pseudoscirpoidea, Jamesia americana, Parnassia parviflora, Pinus flexilis, Salix brachycarpa, </i>and <i>S. nivalis</i>. A third location is the Virginia Lakes Basin northeast of Yosemite National Park on marble (UC accession 1598493) growing with <i>Carex subnigricans </i>and <i>C. tiogana</i>. <i>The Jepson Manual </i>(Hickman 1993) uses the name <i>K. bellardii</i>. <br/>
<br/>
Stands with <i>K. myosuroides </i>may represent one of the rarest alliances in the state. The alliance commonly occurs on windswept ridges below exposed ridge tops at subalpine and alpine elevations in the Rocky Mountains and Cascades. A rarer form of the alliance involves stands found in rich, calcareous fens in Colorado, the <i>Kobresia myosuroides-Thalictrum alpinum </i>association (Carsey et al. 2003). <br/>
<br/>
Cooper and Wolf (2006) sampled fen settings on marble in the Convict Creek watershed, providing this alliance description. Major and Taylor (1977) included <i>K. myosuroides </i>and other disjunct taxa in a <i>Carex subnigricans-Pedicularis attollens </i>type using data from the Convict Creek area (see Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). The Carsey et al. (2003) and Cooper and Wolf (2006) data share the following plants: <i>Juncus arcticus, K. myosuroides, Salix brachycarpa, </i>and <i>Thalictrum alpinum</i>. Cooper and Wolf found <i>C. scirpoidea </i>ssp. <i>pseudoscirpoidea </i>and <i>Trichophorum pumilum </i>without <i>K. myosuroides </i>in a nearby fen. We need to sample and analyze fen vegetation types throughout the high Sierra Nevada to better understand their relationships. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
